The representative at the cash register was rude and condescending. It seemed as if she was bothered that my partner and I went in to even place an order. It seemed like it was too much work for her to enter what toppings we wanted on the burger. She was also too busy flirting with her coworker who seemed to be on break to take our order. I went to the section where we pick up our food and there was a representative who was putting the fries in cups and handing people their orders. There was one order she called that didn’t answer right away. When the person for that order turned up, she looked at the girl and said “oh so you just didn’t see me calling your number when you’re right in my face?” The customer grabbed her stuff and left. One of her coworkers (the person cooking the burgers) told her to relax. The rep who was rude proceeded on saying that the customer got her upset. (The customer did nothing wrong). Things like this is what drives customers away from businesses. This not how you conduct a business. In the middle of a pandemic, you have people who wish they were in the position she was in, being employed. There are so many people who are jobless and need jobs. She clearly doesn’t care for her job.

Okay, so I've finally eaten at Five Guys Burgers...and I like it...but I was expecting more, actually -- patties are shockingly thin (really about the same size as McDonald's and Burger King, only they double 'em here) but sure, they're tasty, okay...like I said, I was just expecting more... certainly they do taste much better than even Burger King on their own...also, the menu's surprisingly short, very, very, very basic...but I guess that's how they're able to pay a living wage (or so they say) to their workers...overall, I rank Five Guys a bit above McD's and BK but below Burger Bandit out in Lynbrook on Long Island... definitely plan on returning here but not as often as I would've thought originally....
